{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2024-01-03","name":"Miles Courcy","nameForms":[{"lang":"und","fullText":"Miles Courcy","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Miles"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"Courcy"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"alternateName":"Baron Kingsale","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1318–1358","fullLifespan":"ABT 1318–1358","birthDate":"+1318","birthPlace":{"address":"Of, Kinsale, Cork, Ireland","geo":{"latitude":51.7075,"longitude":-8.53056,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1358","userCertifiedLifeSummary":"Biography\nMiles de Courcy's father was Miles de Courcy\n\nMiles de Courcy, Lord Courcy, succeeded his father Miles de Courcy, 5th or 6th Lord Courcy in 1338. He sat in the Irish Parliament in 1339.\n\nNumbering from the first, feudal barons of Kinsale, Miles de Courcy was 6th or 7th in succession according to the list provided by the \"Complete Peerage\" \n\nMiles was the sixth Lord of Kingsale, lived in the reigns of Edward II and III\n\nCracroft notes: a Commissioner to treat with MacDermot 1346; a justice of the peace in co. Cork 1355; his coheirs were his four sisters or their issue.\n\nMiles [de Courcy], 2nd Baron Kinsale married Honora O'Brien.\n\nHonora O'Brien was the wife of Miles De Courcy, who died in 1358.\n\n\"John de Courcy having become lord of Kinsale and also of the adjoining castle of Ringrone, was succeeded in his estates by his grandson Milo [Miles], who near the latter place defeated Florence McCarty More and a large party of his followers, and drove them into the river Bandon, where many of them were drowned.\"","events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1318","date":"ABT 1318","place":"Of, Kinsale, Cork, Ireland"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1330","date":"1330","place":"Cork, County Cork, Ireland","age":"12","id":"LZJP-J7P"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1344","date":"6 December 1344","place":"Kinsale, Cork, Munster, Ireland","a